  "prompt": "Why does Obama say ISIL instead of ISIS?",
  "response": "Barack Obama and other officials in his administration often used the term \"ISIL\" (Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant) instead of \"ISIS\" (Islamic State of Iraq and Syria) for specific reasons. One primary reason is that \"Levant\" refers to a broader geographical region that includes not only Syria and Iraq but also parts of Lebanon, Jordan, Israel, and Palestine. By using \"ISIL,\" the intent was to emphasize the group's ambitions beyond just Iraq and Syria, highlighting their broader regional aspirations.\n\nAdditionally, some officials preferred \"ISIL\" to avoid giving the organization legitimacy by using the term \"Islamic State,\" which they argued misrepresented the group's nature. By using \"ISIL,\" they aimed to downplay the notion that it represented a legitimate state or Islamic authority.\n\nIn summary, the choice of terminology reflects both strategic communication considerations and a desire to frame the group's identity and ambitions in a specific way.",
